1) what is the difference between useradd and adduser :
-> both of these commands done the same thing but adduser creates /home directory for user and it also takes all the user information. then useradd is quick way of creating the user and it will not ask the user info and doesnot create the home directory.

if you want to create the user and dont want to take the user inputs we can use the useradd.
it is more useful for when we write the shell scripts.


3) can we restore the user password ?
no we cant restore the password of the user at any cost. because it is highly encrypted.



how to set expiry for the password : chage -M 90 username

how to lock the user account   : passwd -l username 

how to unlock the user account : passwd -u username 


GROUPS :
for example i have the 500 users in the company 250 is dev and 200 QE 30 devOps and 30 management 
one fine day you are a Linux admin they are asked to change the particular file permissions for the 250 developers.
remove the /sbin folder access to that 250 dev 

so to avoid that situation we have to create the groups like dev , QE , devops , management 
we will put the all 250 dev in dev group.
then we can modify the permissions for the group.

how to create the group : groupadd devops 
how to check     : cat /etc/group
how to add user to group : usermod -aG devops pavan 


